    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-07-16T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-07-16T16:00:00-05:00" n="415"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d415">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">674.84A/7–1651: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in Egypt</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d415fn1">Repeated for information to London, Paris, Tel
                        Aviv, and New York; sent by air to Jidda, Baghdad, Ankara, Damascus, Beirut,
                        and Amman.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-07-16T17:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 16, 1951—5 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>73. 1. During call on <persName corresp="#p_MGC2">McGhee</persName> Jul 13 Egypt
                        <gloss target="#t_Amb1">Amb</gloss> on own initiative urged Dept find way
                    postpone <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> consideration Suez restrictions on
                    basis this worst possible time debate such explosive question in view Iran
                    question and delicacy Anglo-Egypt relations. <persName corresp="#p_MGC2"
                        >McGhee</persName> replied only hope postponement wld be voluntary action
                    now by Egypt Govt to lift restrictions. While US not anxious this matter come
                    before <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss>, failure Egypt Govt raise restrictions
                    made <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> consideration unavoidable.</p>
                <p>2. Egypt <gloss target="#t_Amb1">Amb</gloss> also stated that if <gloss
                        target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> called on Egypt re restrictions there was
                    possibility Egypt Govt might not comply as other States did not find compliance
                    necessary. <persName corresp="#p_MGC2">McGhee</persName> emphasized irreparable
                    damage to Egypts position in world councils if such attitude adopted.</p>
                <p>3. Dept wld appreciate ur estimate re Egypts compliance with <gloss
                        target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> res calling for raising of restrictions.<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d415fn2">
                        <p>In telegram 62 from Cairo, July 18, Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_CJ1"
                                >Caffery</persName> replied as follows:</p>
                        <p>“I do not believe that Egyptian conscience wld be greatly troubled by
                            defying possible <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> Resolution on Suez
                            Canal restrictions. They wld undoubtedly cite as justification past
                            instances of Israeli non-compliance with <gloss target="#t_SC1"
                                >SC</gloss> Resolutions. Also they wld be influenced by Iran
                            flouting Hague Court.” (674.84A/7–1851)</p>
                    </note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_ADG1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
